Which one do you prefer? Old or New?

@emilyoberman and team have collaborated with @warnerbrosentertainment on a new brand identity and brand strategy that draws on the company‚Äôs incredible heritage to position it for the future, looking ahead to the studio‚Äôs centennial in 2023. The project updates the iconic ‚ÄúWB‚Äù shield and makes it the foundation of a comprehensive identity system, including a custom typeface inspired by the logo.
.
The Warner Bros. shield is one of the most iconic logos in the world, visual shorthand for entertainment recognized around the globe. The update streamlines the logo to its key elements, refining the shield with a form based on the classical proportions of the golden ratio. The designers looked at the construction of the letterforms of the monogram, preserving their quirkiness but making them more modern. The letters align as though made in one continuous gesture, emphasizing unity and connection.
.
The logo has been optimized to perform across various platforms and scales, from the small spaces of the digital world to large installations like the water tower on the Warner Bros. studio lot. A dimensional version of the logo is used exclusively for on-screen content and special cases. The logo can be customized for the opening and closing moments of individual movies and shows.
.
The monogram has been expanded into a custom typeface, Warner Bros. Condensed Bold, designed by Pentagram and expanded into a full family of fonts by @mckltype. Like the redrawn logo, the typeface carries a sense of the company‚Äôs history, but is clean, modern and timeless.
.
Project team: @timothycohan @artsandmorrison @tom_with_a_k @toddiangoldstein @lisa.grant.nyc .

I‚Äôve just posted this over on the @paintersnetwork_sw account. @papergoldsworthy and I are doing alternate posts each day for a week

Yesterday, I went for a walk by the small river near where I live. It was so I could think about today‚Äôs post. I lived on water for most of my childhood- the Grand Union Canal, in London. So I‚Äôm always drawn to water. I thought about Solaris and how I came to it as a film first- the Tarkovsky version (see clip, sound off) then the book. Solaris explores memory, water and the subconscious whilst the narrator is alone on a space station. It is a wonderful piece of Sci-fi exploring its imaginary landscape and the landscape of memory. This led me to the poet Alice Oswald who wrote Dart. The poem starts from the river‚Äôs origin. I saw Oswald perform live during a panel discussion in 2018. Her rhythm and pace were phenomenal, flawless. She performed a new work from memory. There is a good short Guardian Podcast (Landscape and Literature) where she recites and discusses the Dart. In a recent podcast discovery (Ask an Artist) I found an interesting interview with the paint-maker Michael Harding. It was so lovely and fascinating to hear about his passion and discovery for the making of his high quality Oil Paints. It is very exciting to know that MH is working on a series of watercolours. I‚Äôve been using watercolours a lot over the past year. I love the clink of my paintbrush as I stir the water, like an oar in water. It is a moment of contemplation as I plan the next move on the paper. The journey of making and experimenting brings me lastly to a book I like to return to when I need to pause and think: Waterlog. Deakin starts his journey in the men‚Äôs pond in Hampstead. I would go with a friend to the ladies pond as a teenager. I had a violin teacher who went every day of the year. She was a tough woman, still going in her 80s throughout the winter. I have yet to find the places I like to go to swim in Somerset, but I‚Äôm in no hurry. I intend to remain here as I am happier reconnecting with nature.

The real #PeakyBlinders!

Economic hardship in England led to a violent youth subculture. Poor youths frequently robbed and pickpocketed men walking on the streets. These efforts were executed through assaults, beatings, stabbings, and manual strangulation.
During the 1890s, youth street gangs consisted of men between the ages of twelve and thirty. The late 1890s saw the organisation of these men into a soft hierarchy.
The most violent of these youth street gangs organised themselves as a singular group known as the "Peaky Blinders", based in Birmingham, that operated from the end of the 19th century until the start of First World War.

Members of this gang wore a signature outfit that included tailored jackets, lapel overcoats, button waistcoats, silk scarves, bell-bottom trousers, leather boots, and peaked flat caps. 
The wives, girlfriends, and mistresses of the gang members were known for wearing lavish clothing. Pearls, silks, and colourful scarves were commonplace.
